<!-- Principle 1 -->
<section class="section" style="background-color: #F0F0F0;">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 style="font-size: clamp(3rem, 10vw, 5rem); color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 1rem;">01.</h2>
    <h3 style="font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 5vw, 2.5rem); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Breaking the Grid</h3>
    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 2rem;">"You must know the grid to break it"</p>
    
    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      The grid system was the foundation of Swiss typography—a mathematical framework ensuring perfect alignment. Swiss Punk acknowledged this foundation, then <span style="background: #FFFF00; padding: 0 4px;">deliberately broke it</span>.
    </p>
    
    <div style="background: #FFFF00; padding: 1.5rem; border: 4px solid #000; margin: 2rem 0;">
      <h4 style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">What This Means:</h4>
      <ul style="list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8; font-size: 1.125rem;">
        <li><strong>Asymmetric layouts</strong> - Not random, but intentional disruption</li>
        <li><strong>Overlapping elements</strong> - Text refuses to stay in columns</li>
        <li><strong>Diagonal alignments</strong> - Breaking horizontal tyranny</li>
        <li><strong>Irregular spacing</strong> - Intuition over mathematics</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Principle 2 -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 style="font-size: clamp(3rem, 10vw, 5rem); color: #0000FF; margin-bottom: 1rem;">02.</h2>
    <h3 style="font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 5vw, 2.5rem); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Typography as Expression</h3>
    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: #0000FF; margin-bottom: 2rem;">"Type is the hero, not invisible"</p>
    
    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      Swiss Punk rejected the idea that typography should be invisible. Instead, it made typography the <strong>star</strong> of the design.
    </p>
    
    <div class="card" style="background: #fff; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      <h5 style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Mixed Typefaces & Weights</h5>
      <p>Combining different fonts—even within single words—to create texture and emphasis.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="card" style="background: #0000FF; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      <h5 style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Diagonal & Rotated Type</h5>
      <p>Text set at angles, creating dynamic movement. Typically 3-15 degrees.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="card" style="background: #fff; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      <h5 style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Stair-Stepped Layouts</h5>
      <p>Text arranged in steps, each word offset vertically. A signature Weingart technique.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Principle 3 -->
<section class="section" style="background-color: #000; color: #fff;">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 style="font-size: clamp(3rem, 10vw, 5rem); color: #FFFF00; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2rem;">03. Layered Composition</h2>
    
    <div class="three-col" style="margin-top: 3rem;">
      <div style="background: #fff; color: #000; padding: 1.5rem; border: 4px solid #000;">
        <h4 style="color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.25rem;">Transparent Overlays</h4>
        <p>Text layered on text, shapes on shapes, creating depth and visual complexity.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div style="background: #FF0000; color: #fff; padding: 1.5rem; border: 4px solid #000;">
        <h4 style="margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.25rem;">Halftone Patterns</h4>
        <p>Using photographic screens as texture, creating grainy surfaces that contrast with sharp type.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div style="background: #fff; color: #000; padding: 1.5rem; border: 4px solid #000;">
        <h4 style="color: #0000FF; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.25rem;">Geometric Shapes</h4>
        <p>Circles, squares, triangles used as structural elements that interact with type.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Principle 4 -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 style="font-size: clamp(3rem, 10vw, 5rem); color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 1rem;">04.</h2>
    <h3 style="font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 5vw, 2.5rem); margin-bottom: 1rem;">Kinetic Energy</h3>
    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 2rem;">"Motion in static design"</p>
    
    <div style="background: #FFFF00; padding: 2rem; border: 4px solid #000; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
      <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.3; margin: 0;">
        Swiss Style was STATIC.<br>
        Swiss Punk is <span style="color: #FF0000;">DYNAMIC</span>.
      </p>
    </div>
    
    <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
      Even though Swiss Punk designs are printed on paper, they feel like they're <strong>moving</strong>. This kinetic quality comes from:
    </p>
    
    <ul style="list-style-type: square; padding-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 2;">
      <li><strong>Angular compositions</strong> that suggest motion</li>
      <li><strong>Diagonal elements</strong> that create visual tension</li>
      <li><strong>Layered transparency</strong> implying depth</li>
      <li><strong>Varied scales</strong> creating push-pull dynamics</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Principle 5 -->
<section class="section" style="background-color: #F0F0F0;">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 style="font-size: clamp(2rem, 8vw, 4rem); color: #0000FF; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
      05. Intuition = Analysis
    </h2>
    
    <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: 700; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
      The most revolutionary principle of all
    </p>
    
    <div class="two-col">
      <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.5rem; border: 4px solid #000;">
        <h3 style="font-size: 1.25rem; color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Swiss Style Said:</h3>
        <p style="font-size: 1.125rem;">Design must be <strong>rational</strong>, <strong>objective</strong>, and <strong>analytical</strong>. Remove emotion. Follow the system.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div style="background: #fff; padding: 1.5rem; border: 4px solid #000;">
        <h3 style="font-size: 1.25rem; color: #0000FF; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Swiss Punk Said:</h3>
        <p style="font-size: 1.125rem;">Design requires <strong>both</strong> analytical thinking <strong>and</strong> intuitive feeling. Trust your gut. Experiment.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div style="background: #fff; padding: 2rem; border: 8px solid #000; box-shadow: 8px 8px 0 #000; margin-top: 3rem; text-align: center;">
      <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; font-style: italic; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        "How many different ways can I see this same old stuff?"
      </p>
      <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: #FF0000; margin: 0;">— Wolfgang Weingart</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

